            <br><P CLASS="post">
              What Ratko Vavic failed to do in the above post was mention that in the VERY FIRST E-MAIL HE SENT TO ME, he accused me of fraud.  He did not approach me in a civil manner and ask for a refund, he didn't say "I already knew all of this stuff so it isn't much use to me" and ask for a refund.  No, the very first e-mail he sent to me accused me of committing fraud.  Why? Because we state that for ONE of the FIVE methods, you need to be at least level 45 to do it.  Well, as it turns out, there is a VERY rare mob that is a bottleneck in the cycle that you cannot solo at level 45.  This does not mean you cannot do the cycle at level 45! It simply means that if this rare mob should indeed spawn, you will need help to kill it to continue the cycle.  For apparently not placing a disclaimer in my auction and on my web page, Mr. Vavic e-mailed me and accused me of fraud, and of course asked for a refund.  When someone approaches me like that, I will not give them a refund purely on principle, even though I'm only saving $5.<br><br>Yes, it is true that in my reply to his e-mail accusing me of fraud, there was one sentence that had "You can't possibly know WTF you are doing" in it.  One of the statements in his e-mail suggested he DOESN'T know WTF he is talking about: he said that "casters do not get invis until level 8." He was criticizing another of our methods, saying we misrepresented those because casters don't get invis until level 8, not level 4! Of course, I set him straight on that issue in a big hurry.  I would think that only complete newbies would make a statement like that.  He was apparently quite insulted by my using the abbreviation "WTF" and he told me he didn't think it was good to treat customers like that.  Even customers who accuse you of fraud Ratko? Ratko then e-mails me back, asking me to spell out WTF for him.  So I did! This guy had a lot of nerve contacting me for the first time for a refund by accusing me of fraud, and had even BIGGER nerve to feel that I had wronged HIM by replying with "WTF" in a sentence.  So yes, I spelled it out to him.<br><br>As to your car AC analogy, you are completely wrong sir.  Here is a proper analogy: you buy a car with AC, and the brochure for the car says the AC will maintain a comfortable, 70 degree temperature.  You drive through Death Valley in 125 degree weather, and the AC is not able to bring the temperature in the car down to 70 degrees.  In 99%+ of conditions, it can though.  By your non-logic Ratko, you should accuse the automobile manufacturer of fraud and tell the public they are running a scam, and demand your money back.  After all, the AC was not able to get the temperature down to 70 degrees during that .0001% of the time when you drive through Death Valley in August at 3pm!! This is irrational, unreasonable nitpicking, nothing more.<br><br>In any case, I clearly did not commit fraud.  However, this post is most certainly, legally, libel.  "Khalidorr's Platinum guide is scam" is the title of the post.  You've accused me of fraud, now please explain how this guide is a scam.  And explain why you posted the part of your e-mail that contains details on one of the methods in Khalidorr's guide.<br><br>Before I saw this post, I killfiled your e-mail address because I was sick of dealing with you.  I planned on killfiling any more e-mail addresses you might have e-mailed me from.  Because of this however, I am not going to let this matter slide.<br><br>Doug Reding<br>PlayerAuctions ID 'platfactory'<br>www.powerleveling.com<br><br>
